```cpp
#include <hexi/dynamic_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
void write_to_dynamic_buffer(hexi::dynamic_buffer<block_size>& buffer, uint32_t header, const std::vector<uint8_t>& data) {
    // Write the header value
    buffer.write(&header, sizeof(header));

    // Write the data array
    if (!data.empty()) {
        buffer.write(data.data(), data.size());
    }
}

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
struct BufferData {
    uint32_t header;
    std::vector<uint8_t> data;
};

BufferData<> read_from_dynamic_buffer(hexi::dynamic_buffer<1024>& buffer, size_t data_length) {
    BufferData<> result;

    // Read the header value
    buffer.read(&result.header, sizeof(result.header));

    // Read the data array
    result.data.resize(data_length);
    if (data_length > 0) {
        buffer.read(result.data.data(), data_length);
    }

    return result;
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **write_to_dynamic_buffer:**
   - Uses `buffer.write()` to write the header value directly
   - Checks if data vector is not empty before writing to avoid unnecessary operations
   - Uses `data.data()` to get a pointer to the underlying array for efficient writing

2. **read_from_dynamic_buffer:**
   - Creates a BufferData object to hold the results
   - Uses `buffer.read()` to read the header value into the result structure
   - Resizes the data vector to accommodate the specified length
   - Uses `result.data.data()` to get a pointer for efficient reading into the vector
   - Returns the populated BufferData object

Both functions properly handle the binary data operations using the Hexi dynamic_buffer API as specified in the reference materials.

